<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathem=
atics">mathematics</a>, an <b>integral</b> is the continuous analog of a <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Summation" title=3D"Summation">sum</=
a>, and is used to calculate <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area"=
 title=3D"Area">areas</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume"=
 title=3D"Volume">volumes</a>, and their generalizations. Integration, the =
process of computing an integral, is one of the two fundamental operations =
of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus" title=3D"Calculus">ca=
lculus</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>a<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> the other being <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derivative" title=3D"Derivative">differe=
ntiation</a>. Integration was initially used to solve problems in mathemati=
cs and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Physics">=
physics</a>, such as finding the <b>area under a curve</b>, or determining =
displacement from velocity. Usage of integration expanded to a wide variety=
 of scientific fields thereafter.
</p><p>A <b>definite integral</b> computes the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Signed_area" title=3D"Signed area">signed area</a> of the regi=
on in the plane that is bounded by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Graph_of_a_function" title=3D"Graph of a function">graph</a> of a give=
n <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Function_(mathematics)" title=3D=
"Function (mathematics)">function</a> between two points in the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_line" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rea=
l line">real line</a>. Conventionally, areas above the horizontal <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coordinate_axis" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Coordinate axis">axis</a> of the plane are positive while areas belo=
w are negative. Integrals also refer to the concept of an <i><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antiderivative" title=3D"Antiderivative">antider=
ivative</a></i>, a function whose <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Derivative" title=3D"Derivative">derivative</a> is the given function; in t=
his case, they are also called <i>indefinite integrals</i>. The <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental_theorem_of_calculus" title=3D"Fun=
damental theorem of calculus">fundamental theorem of calculus</a> relates d=
efinite integration to differentiation and provides a method to compute the=
 definite integral of a function when its antiderivative is known; differen=
tiation and integration are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Invers=
e_function" title=3D"Inverse function">inverse</a> operations.
</p><p>Although methods of calculating areas and volumes dated from <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Greek_mathematics" title=3D"Ancie=
nt Greek mathematics">ancient Greek mathematics</a>, the principles of inte=
gration were formulated independently by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Isaac_Newton" title=3D"Isaac Newton">Isaac Newton</a> and <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz" title=3D"Gottfrie=
d Wilhelm Leibniz">Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz</a> in the late 17th century, =
who thought of the area under a curve as an infinite sum of rectangles of <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinitesimal" title=3D"Infinitesim=
al">infinitesimal</a> width. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernh=
ard_Riemann" title=3D"Bernhard Riemann">Bernhard Riemann</a> later gave a r=
igorous definition of integrals, which is based on a limiting procedure tha=
t approximates the area of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curvi=
linear_coordinates" title=3D"Curvilinear coordinates">curvilinear</a> regio=
n by breaking the region into infinitesimally thin vertical slabs. In the e=
arly 20th century, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henri_Lebesgue"=
 title=3D"Henri Lebesgue">Henri Lebesgue</a> generalized Riemann's formulat=
ion by introducing what is now referred to as the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Lebesgue_integration" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Lebesg=
ue integration">Lebesgue integral</a>; it is more general than Riemann's in=
 the sense that a wider class of functions are Lebesgue-integrable.
</p><p>Integrals may be generalized depending on the type of the function a=
s well as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Domain_(mathematical=
_analysis)" title=3D"Domain (mathematical analysis)">domain</a> over which =
the integration is performed. For example, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Line_integral" title=3D"Line integral">line integral</a> is defi=
ned for functions of two or more variables, and the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Interval_(mathematics)" title=3D"Interval (mathematics)">=
interval</a> of integration is replaced by a curve connecting two points in=
 space. In a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_integral" tit=
le=3D"Surface integral">surface integral</a>, the curve is replaced by a pi=
ece of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_(mathematics)" ti=
tle=3D"Surface (mathematics)">surface</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Three-dimensional_space" title=3D"Three-dimensional space">three=
-dimensional space</a>.
</p>
