<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Pre-calculus_integration">P=
re-calculus integration</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DIntegral&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit secti=
on: Pre-calculus integration"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The first documented systematic technique capable of determining integra=
ls is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Method_of_exhaustion" ti=
tle=3D"Method of exhaustion">method of exhaustion</a> of the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Greece" title=3D"Ancient Greece">ancient=
 Greek</a> astronomer <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eudoxus_of_C=
nidus" title=3D"Eudoxus of Cnidus">Eudoxus</a> and philosopher <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Democritus" title=3D"Democritus">Democritus</a=
> (<i>ca.</i> 370 BC), which sought to find areas and volumes by breaking t=
hem up into an infinite number of divisions for which the area or volume wa=
s known.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This method was further d=
eveloped and employed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archimede=
s" title=3D"Archimedes">Archimedes</a> in the 3rd century BC and used to ca=
lculate the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area_of_a_circle" titl=
e=3D"Area of a circle">area of a circle</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Surface_area" title=3D"Surface area">surface area</a> and <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume" title=3D"Volume">volume</a> =
of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sphere" title=3D"Sphere">sphe=
re</a>, area of an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellipse" title=
=3D"Ellipse">ellipse</a>, the area under a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Parabola" title=3D"Parabola">parabola</a>, the volume of a segment=
 of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paraboloid" title=3D"Parabol=
oid">paraboloid</a> of revolution, the volume of a segment of a <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperboloid" title=3D"Hyperboloid">hyperboloi=
d</a> of revolution, and the area of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Spiral" title=3D"Spiral">spiral</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-3"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p><p>A similar method was independently developed in <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/China" title=3D"China">China</a> around the 3rd centur=
y AD by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liu_Hui" title=3D"Liu Hui"=
>Liu Hui</a>, who used it to find the area of the circle. This method was l=
ater used in the 5th century by Chinese father-and-son mathematicians <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zu_Chongzhi" title=3D"Zu Chongzhi">Zu C=
hongzhi</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zu_Geng_(mathemati=
cian)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Zu Geng (mathematician)">Zu Geng</a> =
to find the volume of a sphere.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-4"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the Middle East, Hasan Ibn al-Haytham, Latinized as <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alhazen" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Alhazen=
">Alhazen</a> (<span title=3D"circa">c.</span><span style=3D"white-space:no=
wrap;">=E2=80=89965</span>&nbsp;=E2=80=93 c.<span style=3D"white-space:nowr=
ap;">=E2=80=891040</span>&nbsp;AD) derived a formula for the sum of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourth_power" title=3D"Fourth power">four=
th powers</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Alhazen determined =
the equations to calculate the area enclosed by the curve represented by <s=
pan class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-m=
ath-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmln=
s=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle y=3Dx^{k=
}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>y</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <msup>
          <mi>x</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>k</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle y=3Dx^{k}}</a=
nnotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/7671c58f963c43ee6c236f3e3ed6c54a9c4bfdae" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:6.672ex; height:3.009ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle y=
=3Dx^{k}}"></span> (which translates to the integral <span class=3D"mwe-mat=
h-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mw=
e-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.o=
rg/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \int x^{k}\,dx}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
