        <mi>x</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \int x^{k}\,d=
x}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/8c636c2d61e234c5306b1682165ab4930b76da88" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.338ex; width:7.932ex; height:5.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \in=
t x^{k}\,dx}"></span> in contemporary notation), for any given non-negative=
 integer value of <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline">=
<span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"displa=
y: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle k}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>k</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle k}</annotatio=
n>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/c3c9a2c7b599b37105512c5d570edc034056dd40" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.211ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle k}"=
></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> He used the results to c=
arry out what would now be called an integration of this function, where th=
e formulae for the sums of integral squares and fourth powers allowed him t=
o calculate the volume of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parabo=
loid" title=3D"Paraboloid">paraboloid</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-7"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup>
</p><p>The next significant advances in integral calculus did not begin to =
appear until the 17th century. At this time, the work of <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bonaventura_Cavalieri" title=3D"Bonaventura Cavalier=
i">Cavalieri</a> with his <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Method_o=
f_indivisibles" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Method of indivisibles">meth=
od of indivisibles</a>, and work by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Pierre_de_Fermat" title=3D"Pierre de Fermat">Fermat</a>, began to lay the=
 foundations of modern calculus,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-8"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
with Cavalieri computing the integrals of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i><=
sup><i>n</i></sup></span> up to degree <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =3D=
 9</span> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cavalieri%27s_quadrat=
ure_formula" title=3D"Cavalieri's quadrature formula">Cavalieri's quadratur=
e formula</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The case <i>n</i> =
=3D =E2=88=921 required the invention of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Function_(mathematics)" title=3D"Function (mathematics)">function<=
/a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_logarithm" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hyperbolic logarithm">hyperbolic logarithm</a>,=
 achieved by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadrature_(mathemati=
cs)" title=3D"Quadrature (mathematics)">quadrature</a> of the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbola" title=3D"Hyperbola">hyperbola</a> in=
 1647.
</p><p>Further steps were made in the early 17th century by <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_Barrow" title=3D"Isaac Barrow">Barrow</a> a=
nd <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evangelista_Torricelli" title=
=3D"Evangelista Torricelli">Torricelli</a>, who provided the first hints of=
 a connection between integration and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Differential_calculus" title=3D"Differential calculus">differentiation<=
/a>. Barrow provided the first proof of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Fundamental_theorem_of_calculus" title=3D"Fundamental theorem of =
calculus">fundamental theorem of calculus</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-=
10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Wallis" title=
=3D"John Wallis">Wallis</a> generalized Cavalieri's method, computing integ=
rals of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> =
to a general power, including negative powers and fractional powers.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Integral#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Leibniz_and_Newton">Leibniz=
 and Newton</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Integral&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Leibniz =
and Newton"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<p>The major advance in integration came in the 17th century with the indep=
endent discovery of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamenta=
l_theorem_of_calculus" title=3D"Fundamental theorem of calculus">fundamenta=
l theorem of calculus</a> by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gottf=
ried_Wilhelm_Leibniz" title=3D"Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz">Leibniz</a> and <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_Newton" title=3D"Isaac Newton=
">Newton</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The theorem demon=
strates a connection between integration and differentiation. This connecti=
on, combined with the comparative ease of differentiation, can be exploited=
 to calculate integrals. In particular, the fundamental theorem of calculus=
 allows one to solve a much broader class of problems. Equal in importance =
is the comprehensive mathematical framework that both Leibniz and Newton de=
veloped. Given the name infinitesimal calculus, it allowed for precise anal=
ysis of functions with continuous domains. This framework eventually became=
 modern <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus" title=3D"Calculu=
s">calculus</a>, whose notation for integrals is drawn directly from the wo=
rk of Leibniz.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Formalization">Formalizatio=
n</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DIntegral&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Formalization"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<p>While Newton and Leibniz provided a systematic approach to integration, =
their work lacked a degree of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rigo=
r#Mathematical_rigour" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rigor">rigour</a>. <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Berkeley" title=3D"George Ber=
keley">Bishop Berkeley</a> memorably attacked the vanishing increments used=
 by Newton, calling them "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Anal=
yst#Content" title=3D"The Analyst">ghosts of departed quantities</a>".<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Integral#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Calculus acquired a firmer footing =
with the development of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_(mat=
hematics)" title=3D"Limit (mathematics)">limits</a>. Integration was first =
rigorously formalized, using limits, by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Bernhard_Riemann" title=3D"Bernhard Riemann">Riemann</a>.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In=
tegral#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Although all bounded <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Piecewise" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Piecewise">pi=
ecewise</a> continuous functions are Riemann-integrable on a bounded interv=
al, subsequently more general functions were considered=E2=80=94particularl=
y in the context of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourier_analys=
is" title=3D"Fourier analysis">Fourier analysis</a>=E2=80=94to which Rieman=
n's definition does not apply, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Henri_Lebesgue" title=3D"Henri Lebesgue">Lebesgue</a> formulated a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#Lebesgue_integral">different def=
inition of integral</a>, founded in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Measure_(mathematics)" title=3D"Measure (mathematics)">measure theory</a>=
 (a subfield of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_analysis" tit=
le=3D"Real analysis">real analysis</a>). Other definitions of integral, ext=
ending Riemann's and Lebesgue's approaches, were proposed. These approaches=
 based on the real number system are the ones most common today, but altern=
ative approaches exist, such as a definition of integral as the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_part" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Standard part">standard part</a> of an infinite Riemann sum, based on the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperreal_number" title=3D"Hyperre=
al number">hyperreal number</a> system.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Historical_notation">Histor=
ical notation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DIntegral&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Histo=
rical notation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<p>The notation for the indefinite integral was introduced by <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz" title=3D"Gottfried W=
ilhelm Leibniz">Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz</a> in 1675.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1=
5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#ci=
te_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> He adapted the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Integral_symbol" title=3D"Integral symbol">integral symbol</a>, <b>=E2=
=88=AB</b>, from the letter <i>=C5=BF</i> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Long_s" title=3D"Long s">long s</a>), standing for <i>summa</i> (w=
ritten as <i>=C5=BFumma</i>; Latin for "sum" or "total"). The modern notati=
on for the definite integral, with limits above and below the integral sign=
, was first used by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Fourier=
" title=3D"Joseph Fourier">Joseph Fourier</a> in <i>M=C3=A9moires</i> of th=
e French Academy around 1819=E2=80=931820, reprinted in his book of 1822.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Integral#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_Newton" title=3D"Isaa=
c Newton">Isaac Newton</a> used a small vertical bar above a variable to in=
dicate integration, or placed the variable inside a box. The vertical bar w=
as easily confused with <span class=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"sfrac nowrap=
;"><span style=3D"display:none; display:inline-block; text-align:center;"><=
span style=3D"display:block; line-height:0.8em; font-size:70%;"><b>.</b></s=
pan><span style=3D"display:block; line-height:1em;"><i>x</i></span></span><=
/span></span> or <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i>=E2=80=B2</span>, which ar=
e used to indicate differentiation, and the box notation was difficult for =
printers to reproduce, so these notations were not widely adopted.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Integral#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"First_use_of_the_term">Firs=
t use of the term</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DIntegral&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Fi=
rst use of the term"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The term was first printed in Latin by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Jacob_Bernoulli" title=3D"Jacob Bernoulli">Jacob Bernoulli</a> in 1=
690: "Ergo et horum Integralia aequantur".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-18">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Terminology_and_notation">T=
erminology and notation</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DIntegral&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit secti=
on: Terminology and notation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In general, the integral of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R=
eal-valued_function" title=3D"Real-valued function">real-valued function</a=
> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>)</span> with respect to a real =
variable <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i></span> on an interval <span class=
=3D"texhtml">[<i>a</i>, <i>b</i>]</span> is written as
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \int _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msubsup>
          <mo>=E2=88=AB<!-- =E2=88=AB --></mo>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>a</mi>
          </mrow>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>b</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msubsup>
        <mi>f</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
