    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \int _{a}^{b}=
f(x)\,dx.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/249ee3fdbced31dfc328ff357f67bb134ca66b8d" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.338ex; width:11.786ex; height:6.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \i=
nt _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx.}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>The integral sign <span class=3D"texhtml">=E2=88=AB</span> represents in=
tegration. The symbol <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>dx</i></span>, called the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_(infinitesimal)" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Differential (infinitesimal)">differential</a> o=
f the variable <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i></span>, indicates that the =
variable of integration is <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i></span>.  The fu=
nction <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>)</span> is called the <i>i=
ntegrand</i>, the points <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span> are called the limits (or bounds) of inte=
gration, and the integral is said to be over the interval <span class=3D"te=
xhtml">[<i>a</i>, <i>b</i>]</span>, called the interval of integration.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-:1_19-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-:1-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
A function is said to be <em>integrable</em><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"In=
tegrable"></span><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Integrable_function"></span> =
if its integral over its domain is finite. If limits are specified, the int=
egral is called a definite integral.
</p><p>When the limits are omitted, as in
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \int f(x)\,dx,}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mo>=E2=88=AB<!-- =E2=88=AB --></mo>
        <mi>f</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mi>d</mi>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \int f(x)\,dx=
,}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/1bbd50daec1c6f3767a42b842a9b203d840e9934" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.338ex; width:10.578ex; height:5.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \i=
nt f(x)\,dx,}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>the integral is called an indefinite integral, which represents a class =
of functions (the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antiderivative" =
title=3D"Antiderivative">antiderivative</a>) whose derivative is the integr=
and.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental_theorem_of_calculus" title=3D"Fundamental th=
eorem of calculus">fundamental theorem of calculus</a> relates the evaluati=
on of definite integrals to indefinite integrals. There are several extensi=
ons of the notation for integrals to encompass integration on unbounded dom=
ains and/or in multiple dimensions (see later sections of this article).
</p><p>In advanced settings, it is not uncommon to leave out <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><i>dx</i></span> when only the simple <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Riemann_integral" title=3D"Riemann integral">Riemann integral=
</a> is being used, or the exact type of integral is immaterial. For instan=
ce, one might write <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline=
"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"disp=
lay: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{=
\textstyle \int _{a}^{b}(c_{1}f+c_{2}g)=3Dc_{1}\int _{a}^{b}f+c_{2}\int _{a=
}^{b}g}">
