een the Riemann integral and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D=
arboux_integral" title=3D"Darboux integral">Darboux integral</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Lebesgue_integral">Lebesgue=
 integral</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DIn=
tegral&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Lebesgue =
integral"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</sp=
an></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lebesgue_integration=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Lebesgue integration">Lebesgue integration=
</a></div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Lebesgueintegralsimplefunctions_finer-dotted.svg" class=3D"mw-file-desc=
ription"><img alt=3D"Comparison of Riemann and Lebesgue integrals" src=3D"h=
ttps://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2f/Lebesgueintegralsi=
mplefunctions_finer-dotted.svg/250px-Lebesgueintegralsimplefunctions_finer-=
dotted.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"79" class=3D"mw-=
file-element" data-file-width=3D"366" data-file-height=3D"116"></a><figcapt=
ion>Lebesgue integration</figcaption></figure>
<p>It is often of interest, both in theory and applications, to be able to =
pass to the limit under the integral. For instance, a sequence of functions=
 can frequently be constructed that approximate, in a suitable sense, the s=
olution to a problem. Then the integral of the solution function should be =
the limit of the integrals of the approximations. However, many functions t=
hat can be obtained as limits are not Riemann-integrable, and so such limit=
 theorems do not hold with the Riemann integral. Therefore, it is of great =
importance to have a definition of the integral that allows a wider class o=
f functions to be integrated.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-24"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Such an integral is the Lebesgue integral, that exploits the followi=
ng fact to enlarge the class of integrable functions: if the values of a fu=
nction are rearranged over the domain, the integral of a function should re=
main the same. Thus <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henri_Lebesgue=
" title=3D"Henri Lebesgue">Henri Lebesgue</a> introduced the integral beari=
ng his name, explaining this integral thus in a letter to <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Montel" title=3D"Paul Montel">Paul Montel</a>:=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>I have to pay a certain sum, which I=
 have collected in my pocket. I take the bills and coins out of my pocket a=
nd give them to the creditor in the order I find them until I have reached =
the total sum. This is the Riemann integral. But I can proceed differently.=
 After I have taken all the money out of my pocket I order the bills and co=
ins according to identical values and then I pay the several heaps one afte=
r the other to the creditor. This is my integral.</p></blockquote>
<p>As Folland puts it, "To compute the Riemann integral of <span class=3D"t=
exhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">f</span>, one partitions the doma=
in <span class=3D"texhtml">[<i>a</i>, <i>b</i>]</span> into subintervals", =
while in the Lebesgue integral, "one is in effect partitioning the range of=
 <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">f</span> ".<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Integral#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The definition of the Lebesgue inte=
gral thus begins with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Measure_(m=
athematics)" title=3D"Measure (mathematics)">measure</a>, =CE=BC. In the si=
mplest case, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lebesgue_measure"=
 title=3D"Lebesgue measure">Lebesgue measure</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i=
>=CE=BC</i>(<i>A</i>)</span> of an interval <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i=
> =3D [<i>a</i>, <i>b</i>]</span> is its width, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
b</i> =E2=88=92 <i>a</i></span>, so that the Lebesgue integral agrees with =
the (proper) Riemann integral when both exist.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-=
27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> In more complicated cases, the sets being measured can be h=
ighly fragmented, with no continuity and no resemblance to intervals.
</p><p>Using the "partitioning the range of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">f</span> " philosophy, the integral of a non-neg=
ative function <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>&nbsp;: <b>R</b> =E2=86=92 <=
b>R</b></span> should be the sum over <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">t</span> of the areas between a thin horizontal strip =
between <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>y</i> =3D <i>t</i></span> and <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><i>y</i> =3D <i>t</i> + <i>dt</i></span>. This area is just <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=BC</i>{ <i>x</i>&nbsp;: <i>f</i>(<i>x</i>) &g=
t; <i>t</i>}=E2=80=89<i>dt</i></span>. Let <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>=
<sup>=E2=88=97</sup>(<i>t</i>) =3D <i>=CE=BC</i>{ <i>x</i>&nbsp;: <i>f</i>(=
<i>x</i>) &gt; <i>t</i> }</span>. The Lebesgue integral of <span class=3D"t=
exhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">f</span> is then defined by
</p>
