and therefore has a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Well-defined" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Well-defined">well-defined</a> improper Riem=
ann integral).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For a suitable c=
lass of functions (the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Measurable_=
function" title=3D"Measurable function">measurable functions</a>) this defi=
nes the Lebesgue integral.
</p><p>A general measurable function <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">f</span> is Lebesgue-integrable if the sum of the absol=
ute values of the areas of the regions between the graph of <span class=3D"=
texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">f</span> and the <span class=3D"=
texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span>-axis is finite:<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Integral#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
