<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Other_integrals">Other inte=
grals</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DIntegr=
al&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Other integra=
ls"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<p>Although the Riemann and Lebesgue integrals are the most widely used def=
initions of the integral, a number of others exist, including:
</p>
<ul><li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Darboux_integral" titl=
e=3D"Darboux integral">Darboux integral</a>, which is defined by Darboux su=
ms (restricted Riemann sums) yet is equivalent to the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riemann_integral" title=3D"Riemann integral">Riemann in=
tegral</a>. A function is Darboux-integrable if and only if it is Riemann-i=
ntegrable. Darboux integrals have the advantage of being easier to define t=
han Riemann integrals.</li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riemann%E2%80%93Stieltjes_=
integral" title=3D"Riemann=E2=80=93Stieltjes integral">Riemann=E2=80=93Stie=
ltjes integral</a>, an extension of the Riemann integral which integrates w=
ith respect to a function as opposed to a variable.</li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lebesgue%E2%80%93Stieltjes=
_integration" title=3D"Lebesgue=E2=80=93Stieltjes integration">Lebesgue=E2=
=80=93Stieltjes integral</a>, further developed by <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Johann_Radon" title=3D"Johann Radon">Johann Radon</a>, whi=
ch generalizes both the Riemann=E2=80=93Stieltjes and Lebesgue integrals.</=
li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daniell_integral" title=3D=
"Daniell integral">Daniell integral</a>, which subsumes the Lebesgue integr=
al and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lebesgue%E2%80%93Stieltjes_=
integration" title=3D"Lebesgue=E2=80=93Stieltjes integration">Lebesgue=E2=
=80=93Stieltjes integral</a> without depending on <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Measure_(mathematics)" title=3D"Measure (mathematics)">meas=
ures</a>.</li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haar_integral" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Haar integral">Haar integral</a>, used for integration =
on locally compact topological groups, introduced by <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfr%C3%A9d_Haar" title=3D"Alfr=C3=A9d Haar">Alfr=C3=A9d=
 Haar</a> in 1933.</li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henstock%E2%80%93Kurzweil_=
integral" title=3D"Henstock=E2=80=93Kurzweil integral">Henstock=E2=80=93Kur=
zweil integral</a>, variously defined by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Arnaud_Denjoy" title=3D"Arnaud Denjoy">Arnaud Denjoy</a>, <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oskar_Perron" title=3D"Oskar Perron">Oskar P=
erron</a>, and (most elegantly, as the gauge integral) <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jaroslav_Kurzweil" title=3D"Jaroslav Kurzweil">Jarosla=
v Kurzweil</a>, and developed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R=
alph_Henstock" title=3D"Ralph Henstock">Ralph Henstock</a>.</li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Khinchin_integral" title=
=3D"Khinchin integral">Khinchin integral</a>, named after <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aleksandr_Khinchin" title=3D"Aleksandr Khinchin">Al=
eksandr Khinchin</a>.</li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/It%C3%B4_integral" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"It=C3=B4 integral">It=C3=B4 integral</a> and <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stratonovich_integral" title=3D"Strato=
novich integral">Stratonovich integral</a>, which define integration with r=
espect to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semimartingale" title=3D=
"Semimartingale">semimartingales</a> such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Wiener_process" title=3D"Wiener process">Brownian motion</a>.</l=
i>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Young_integral" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Young integral">Young integral</a>, which is a kind of=
 Riemann=E2=80=93Stieltjes integral with respect to certain functions of <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bounded_variation" title=3D"Bounded =
variation">unbounded variation</a>.</li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rough_path" title=3D"Rough=
 path">rough path</a> integral, which is defined for functions equipped wit=
h some additional "rough path" structure and generalizes stochastic integra=
tion against both <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semimartingale" =
title=3D"Semimartingale">semimartingales</a> and processes such as the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fractional_Brownian_motion" title=3D"F=
ractional Brownian motion">fractional Brownian motion</a>.</li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Choquet_integral" title=3D=
"Choquet integral">Choquet integral</a>, a subadditive or superadditive int=
egral created by the French mathematician Gustave Choquet in 1953.</li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bochner_integral" title=3D=
"Bochner integral">Bochner integral</a>, a generalization of the Lebesgue i=
ntegral to functions that take values in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Banach_space" title=3D"Banach space">Banach space</a>.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Properties">Properties</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DIntegral&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Properties"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Linearity">Linearity</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DIntegral&amp;actio=
n=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: Linearity"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The collection of Riemann-integrable functions on a closed interval <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml">[<i>a</i>, <i>b</i>]</span> forms a <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_space" title=3D"Vector space">vector space</a>=
 under the operations of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pointwise=
_addition" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pointwise addition">pointwise add=
ition</a> and multiplication by a scalar, and the operation of integration
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e f\mapsto \int _{a}^{b}f(x)\;dx}">
