<p>A "proper" Riemann integral assumes the integrand is defined and finite =
on a closed and bounded interval, bracketed by the limits of integration. A=
n improper integral occurs when one or more of these conditions is not sati=
sfied. In some cases such integrals may be defined by considering the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_(mathematics)" title=3D"Limit (ma=
thematics)">limit</a> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sequenc=
e" title=3D"Sequence">sequence</a> of proper <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Riemann_integral" title=3D"Riemann integral">Riemann integrals</=
a> on progressively larger intervals.
</p><p>If the interval is unbounded, for instance at its upper end, then th=
e improper integral is the limit as that endpoint goes to infinity:<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Integral#cite_note-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
