<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Line_integrals_and_surface_=
integrals">Line integrals and surface integrals</h3><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DIntegral&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D23" title=3D"Edit section: Line integrals and surface integrals"><span>e=
dit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line_integral" titl=
e=3D"Line integral">Line integral</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Surface_integral" title=3D"Surface integral">Surface integral</a></=
div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Line-Integral.gif" class=3D"m=
w-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/comm=
ons/thumb/d/d8/Line-Integral.gif/250px-Line-Integral.gif" decoding=3D"async=
" width=3D"250" height=3D"229" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D=
"300" data-file-height=3D"275"></a><figcaption>A line integral sums togethe=
r elements along a curve.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The concept of an integral can be extended to more general domains of in=
tegration, such as curved lines and surfaces inside higher-dimensional spac=
es. Such integrals are known as line integrals and surface integrals respec=
tively. These have important applications in physics, as when dealing with =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_field" title=3D"Vector fiel=
d">vector fields</a>.
</p><p>A <i>line integral</i> (sometimes called a <i>path integral</i>) is =
an integral where the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Function_(ma=
thematics)" title=3D"Function (mathematics)">function</a> to be integrated =
is evaluated along a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curve" title=
=3D"Curve">curve</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-43" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-43"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Various d=
ifferent line integrals are in use. In the case of a closed curve it is als=
o called a <i>contour integral</i>.
</p><p>The function to be integrated may be a <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Scalar_field" title=3D"Scalar field">scalar field</a> or a <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_field" title=3D"Vector field">v=
ector field</a>. The value of the line integral is the sum of values of the=
 field at all points on the curve, weighted by some scalar function on the =
curve (commonly <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arc_length" title=
=3D"Arc length">arc length</a> or, for a vector field, the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inner_product_space" title=3D"Inner product space"=
>scalar product</a> of the vector field with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Differential_(infinitesimal)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"D=
ifferential (infinitesimal)">differential</a> vector in the curve).<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-44" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Integral#cite_note-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This weighting distinguishes the line=
 integral from simpler integrals defined on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Interval_(mathematics)" title=3D"Interval (mathematics)">interval=
s</a>. Many simple formulas in physics have natural continuous analogs in t=
erms of line integrals; for example, the fact that <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Mechanical_work" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mechanical=
 work">work</a> is equal to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Force"=
 title=3D"Force">force</a>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>F</b></span>, multip=
lied by displacement, <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>s</b></span>, may be expre=
ssed (in terms of vector quantities) as:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-45" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-45"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e W=3D\mathbf {F} \cdot \mathbf {s} .}">
