\mathbf {F} \cdot d\mathbf {s} .}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/9d831488a8fe259c861dc13cb61643918fd70f56" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.338ex; width:14.975ex; height:5.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle W=
=3D\int _{C}\mathbf {F} \cdot d\mathbf {s} .}"></span></dd></dl>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Surface_integral_illustration=
.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.or=
g/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/72/Surface_integral_illustration.svg/250px-Surf=
ace_integral_illustration.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=
=3D"170" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"512" data-file-height=
=3D"348"></a><figcaption>The definition of surface integral relies on split=
ting the surface into small surface elements.</figcaption></figure>
<p>A <i>surface integral</i> generalizes double integrals to integration ov=
er a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_(mathematics)" title=
=3D"Surface (mathematics)">surface</a> (which may be a curved set in <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Space" title=3D"Space">space</a>); it ca=
n be thought of as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiple_in=
tegral" title=3D"Multiple integral">double integral</a> analog of the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line_integral" title=3D"Line integral">=
line integral</a>. The function to be integrated may be a <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scalar_field" title=3D"Scalar field">scalar field</=
a> or a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_field" title=3D"Vec=
tor field">vector field</a>. The value of the surface integral is the sum o=
f the field at all points on the surface. This can be achieved by splitting=
 the surface into surface elements, which provide the partitioning for Riem=
ann sums.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>For an example of applications of surface integrals, consider a vect=
or field <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>v</b></span> on a surface <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>S</i></span>; that is, for each point <span class=3D"texhtm=
l"><i>x</i></span> in <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>S</i></span>, <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><b>v</b>(<i>x</i>)</span> is a vector. Imagine that a fluid fl=
ows through <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>S</i></span>, such that <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><b>v</b>(<i>x</i>)</span> determines the velocity of the fluid=
 at <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span>. The=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux" title=3D"Flux">flux</a> is =
defined as the quantity of fluid flowing through <span class=3D"texhtml"><i=
>S</i></span> in unit amount of time. To find the flux, one need to take th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dot_product" title=3D"Dot produc=
t">dot product</a> of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>v</b></span> with the unit=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_(geometry)" title=3D"Norma=
l (geometry)">surface normal</a> to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>S</i></span>=
 at each point, which will give a scalar field, which is integrated over th=
e surface:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \int _{S}{\mathbf {v} }\cdot \,d{\mathbf {S} }.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mo>=E2=88=AB<!-- =E2=88=AB --></mo>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>S</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">v</mi>
          </mrow>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=E2=8B=85<!-- =E2=8B=85 --></mo>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mi>d</mi>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">S</mi>
          </mrow>
        </mrow>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \int _{S}{\ma=
thbf {v} }\cdot \,d{\mathbf {S} }.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/27a969275a87437b804ded78fb9b02d57ce1dbbf" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.338ex; width:9.797ex; height:5.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \in=
t _{S}{\mathbf {v} }\cdot \,d{\mathbf {S} }.}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>The fluid flux in this example may be from a physical fluid such as wate=
r or air, or from electrical or magnetic flux. Thus surface integrals have =
applications in physics, particularly with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Classical_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Classical the=
ory">classical theory</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elect=
romagnetism" title=3D"Electromagnetism">electromagnetism</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Contour_integrals">Contour =
integrals</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DIn=
tegral&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D24" title=3D"Edit section: Contour i=
ntegrals"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</sp=
an></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Contour_integration"=
 title=3D"Contour integration">Contour integration</a></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_analysis" title=3D"C=
omplex analysis">complex analysis</a>, the integrand is a <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex-valued_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Complex-valued function">complex-valued function</a> of a complex vari=
able <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">z</span> ins=
tead of a real function of a real variable <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" sty=
le=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span>. When a complex function is integrated a=
long a curve <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span=
 class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: no=
ne;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displa=
ystyle \gamma }">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>=CE=B3<!-- =CE=B3 --></mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \gamma }</ann=
otation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/a223c880b0ce3da8f64ee33c4f0010beee400b1a" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:1.262ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \ga=
mma }"></span> in the complex plane, the integral is denoted as follows
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \int _{\gamma }f(z)\,dz.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mo>=E2=88=AB<!-- =E2=88=AB --></mo>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>=CE=B3<!-- =CE=B3 --></mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mi>f</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>z</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mi>d</mi>
        <mi>z</mi>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \int _{\gamma=
 }f(z)\,dz.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/adf4ad465dcdd2fddac974923eaa3ed1913186e8" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.671ex; width:10.318ex; height:6.009ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \i=
nt _{\gamma }f(z)\,dz.}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>This is known as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Contour_inte=
gral" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Contour integral">contour integral</a>=
.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Integrals_of_differential_f=
orms">Integrals of differential forms</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DIntegral&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D25" titl=
e=3D"Edit section: Integrals of differential forms"><span>edit</span></a><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_form" t=
itle=3D"Differential form">Differential form</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume_form" title=3D"Vo=
lume form">Volume form</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Den=
sity_on_a_manifold" title=3D"Density on a manifold">Density on a manifold</=
a></div>
<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_form" title=3D"D=
ifferential form">differential form</a> is a mathematical concept in the fi=
elds of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multivariable_calculus" ti=
tle=3D"Multivariable calculus">multivariable calculus</a>, <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_topology" title=3D"Differential topol=
ogy">differential topology</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Tensor" title=3D"Tensor">tensors</a>. Differential forms are organized by=
 degree. For example, a one-form is a weighted sum of the differentials of =
the coordinates, such as:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e E(x,y,z)\,dx+F(x,y,z)\,dy+G(x,y,z)\,dz}">
