</p><p>Unlike the cross product, and the three-dimensional vector calculus,=
 the wedge product and the calculus of differential forms makes sense in ar=
bitrary dimension and on more general manifolds (curves, surfaces, and thei=
r higher-dimensional analogs). The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
