<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Summations">Summations</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DIntegral&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D26" title=3D"Edit section: Summations"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Summation#Approximat=
ion_by_definite_integrals" title=3D"Summation">Summation =C2=A7&nbsp;Approx=
imation by definite integrals</a></div>
<p>The discrete equivalent of integration is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Summation" title=3D"Summation">summation</a>. Summations and int=
egrals can be put on the same foundations using the theory of <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lebesgue_integral" title=3D"Lebesgue integral">=
Lebesgue integrals</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time-sca=
le_calculus" title=3D"Time-scale calculus">time-scale calculus</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Functional_integrals">Funct=
ional integrals</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DIntegral&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=3D"Edit section: Fun=
ctional integrals"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_integrati=
on" title=3D"Functional integration">Functional integration</a></div>
<p>An integration that is performed not over a variable (or, in physics, ov=
er a space or time dimension), but over a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Function_space" title=3D"Function space">space of functions</a>, is=
 referred to as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_integ=
ral" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Functional integral">functional integra=
l</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DIntegral&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" title=3D"Edit section: Applications"><span=
>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div=
>
<p>Integrals are used extensively in many areas. For example, in <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_theory" title=3D"Probability the=
ory">probability theory</a>, integrals are used to determine the probabilit=
y of some <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_variable" title=
=3D"Random variable">random variable</a> falling within a certain range.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Integral#cite_note-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Moreover, the integral under an e=
ntire <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_density_function=
" title=3D"Probability density function">probability density function</a> m=
ust equal 1, which provides a test of whether a <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Function_(mathematics)" title=3D"Function (mathematics)">func=
tion</a> with no negative values could be a density function or not.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-50" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Integral#cite_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Integrals can be used for computing the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Area" title=3D"Area">area</a> of a two-dimensional region that=
 has a curved boundary, as well as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Volume_integral" title=3D"Volume integral">computing the volume</a> of a t=
hree-dimensional object that has a curved boundary. The area of a two-dimen=
sional region can be calculated using the aforementioned definite integral.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The volume of a three-dimensio=
