<p>Integrals are also used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ther=
modynamics" title=3D"Thermodynamics">thermodynamics</a>, where <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thermodynamic_integration" title=3D"Thermodyna=
mic integration">thermodynamic integration</a> is used to calculate the dif=
ference in free energy between two given states.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Computation">Computation</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DIntegral&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D29" title=3D"Edit section: Computation"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Analytical">Analytical</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DIntegral&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D30" title=3D"Edit section: Analytical"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The most basic technique for computing definite integrals of one real va=
riable is based on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental=
_theorem_of_calculus" title=3D"Fundamental theorem of calculus">fundamental=
 theorem of calculus</a>. Let <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>)</s=
pan> be the function of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">x</span> to be integrated over a given interval <span class=3D"texht=
ml">[<i>a</i>, <i>b</i>]</span>. Then, find an antiderivative of <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">f</span>; that is, a functi=
on <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">F</span> such =
that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i>=E2=80=B2 =3D <i>f</i></span> on the i=
nterval. Provided the integrand and integral have no <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_singularity" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Mathematical singularity">singularities</a> on the path of integration, by=
 the fundamental theorem of calculus,
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \int _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx=3DF(b)-F(a).}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msubsup>
          <mo>=E2=88=AB<!-- =E2=88=AB --></mo>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>a</mi>
          </mrow>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>b</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msubsup>
        <mi>f</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mi>d</mi>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>F</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>b</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mi>F</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>a</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \int _{a}^{b}=
f(x)\,dx=3DF(b)-F(a).}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/4f470e7743fda04c3d353a4dee2f441ae454f528" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.338ex; width:27.052ex; height:6.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \i=
nt _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx=3DF(b)-F(a).}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>Sometimes it is necessary to use one of the many techniques that have be=
en developed to evaluate integrals. Most of these techniques rewrite one in=
tegral as a different one which is hopefully more tractable. Techniques inc=
lude <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integration_by_substitution" =
title=3D"Integration by substitution">integration by substitution</a>, <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integration_by_parts" title=3D"Integra=
tion by parts">integration by parts</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Trigonometric_substitution" title=3D"Trigonometric substitution">int=
egration by trigonometric substitution</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Partial_fractions_in_integration" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Partial fractions in integration">integration by partial fractions</a>.
</p><p>Alternative methods exist to compute more complex integrals. Many <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nonelementary_integral" title=3D"Non=
elementary integral">nonelementary integrals</a> can be expanded in a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taylor_series" title=3D"Taylor series">=
Taylor series</a> and integrated term by term. Occasionally, the resulting =
infinite series can be summed analytically. The method of convolution using=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meijer_G-function" title=3D"Meije=
r G-function">Meijer G-functions</a> can also be used, assuming that the in=
tegrand can be written as a product of Meijer G-functions. There are also m=
any less common ways of calculating definite integrals; for instance, <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parseval%27s_identity" title=3D"Parseva=
l's identity">Parseval's identity</a> can be used to transform an integral =
over a rectangular region into an infinite sum. Occasionally, an integral c=
an be evaluated by a trick; for an example of this, see <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaussian_integral" title=3D"Gaussian integral">Gaussi=
an integral</a>.
</p><p>Computations of volumes of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Solid_of_revolution" title=3D"Solid of revolution">solids of revolution</a>=
 can usually be done with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disk_int=
egration" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Disk integration">disk integration=
</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shell_integration" title=
=3D"Shell integration">shell integration</a>.
</p><p>Specific results which have been worked out by various techniques ar=
e collected in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lists_of_integr=
als" title=3D"Lists of integrals">list of integrals</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Symbolic">Symbolic</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DIntegral&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D31" title=3D"Edit section: Symbolic"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symbolic_integration=
" title=3D"Symbolic integration">Symbolic integration</a></div>
<p>Many problems in mathematics, physics, and engineering involve integrati=
on where an explicit formula for the integral is desired. Extensive <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lists_of_integrals" title=3D"Lists of int=
egrals">tables of integrals</a> have been compiled and published over the y=
ears for this purpose. With the spread of computers, many professionals, ed=
ucators, and students have turned to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Computer_algebra_system" title=3D"Computer algebra system">computer alge=
bra systems</a> that are specifically designed to perform difficult or tedi=
ous tasks, including integration. Symbolic integration has been one of the =
motivations for the development of the first such systems, like <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Macsyma" title=3D"Macsyma">Macsyma</a> and <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maple_(software)" title=3D"Maple (so=
ftware)">Maple</a>.
</p><p>A major mathematical difficulty in symbolic integration is that in m=
any cases, a relatively simple function does not have integrals that can be=
 expressed in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Closed-form_expressi=
on" title=3D"Closed-form expression">closed form</a> involving only <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elementary_function" title=3D"Elementary =
function">elementary functions</a>, include <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Rational_function" title=3D"Rational function">rational</a> and <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_function" title=3D"Expo=
nential function">exponential</a> functions, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Logarithm" title=3D"Logarithm">logarithm</a>, <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trigonometric_functions" title=3D"Trigonometric func=
tions">trigonometric functions</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Inverse_trigonometric_functions" title=3D"Inverse trigonometric functi=
ons">inverse trigonometric functions</a>, and the operations of multiplicat=
ion and composition. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Risch_alg=
orithm" title=3D"Risch algorithm">Risch algorithm</a> provides a general cr=
iterion to determine whether the antiderivative of an elementary function i=
s elementary and to compute the integral if is elementary. However, functio=
ns with closed expressions of antiderivatives are the exception, and conseq=
uently, computerized algebra systems have no hope of being able to find an =
antiderivative for a randomly constructed elementary function. On the posit=
ive side, if the 'building blocks' for antiderivatives are fixed in advance=
, it may still be possible to decide whether the antiderivative of a given =
function can be expressed using these blocks and operations of multiplicati=
on and composition and to find the symbolic answer whenever it exists. The =
Risch algorithm, implemented in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ma=
thematica" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mathematica">Mathematica</a>, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maple_(software)" title=3D"Maple (sof=
tware)">Maple</a> and other <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comput=
er_algebra_system" title=3D"Computer algebra system">computer algebra syste=
ms</a>, does just that for functions and antiderivatives built from rationa=
l functions, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nth_root" title=3D"Nt=
h root">radicals</a>, logarithm, and exponential functions.
</p><p>Some special integrands occur often enough to warrant special study.=
 In particular, it may be useful to have, in the set of antiderivatives, th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special_functions" title=3D"Spec=
ial functions">special functions</a> (like the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Legendre_function" title=3D"Legendre function">Legendre functi=
ons</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypergeometric_functi=
on" title=3D"Hypergeometric function">hypergeometric function</a>, the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gamma_function" title=3D"Gamma functio=
n">gamma function</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Incompl=
ete_gamma_function" title=3D"Incomplete gamma function">incomplete gamma fu=
nction</a> and so on). Extending Risch's algorithm to include such function=
s is possible but challenging and has been an active research subject.
</p><p>More recently a new approach has emerged, using <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/D-finite_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"D-fi=
nite function"> <i>D</i>-finite functions</a>, which are the solutions of <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_differential_equation" title=
=3D"Linear differential equation">linear differential equations</a> with po=
lynomial coefficients. Most of the elementary and special functions are <i>=
D</i>-finite, and the integral of a <i>D</i>-finite function is also a <i>D=
</i>-finite function. This provides an algorithm to express the antiderivat=
ive of a <i>D</i>-finite function as the solution of a differential equatio=
n. This theory also allows one to compute the definite integral of a <i>D</=
i>-function as the sum of a series given by the first coefficients and prov=
ides an algorithm to compute any coefficient.
</p><p>Rule-based integration systems facilitate integration.  Rubi, a comp=
uter algebra system rule-based integrator, pattern matches an extensive sys=
tem of symbolic integration rules to integrate a wide variety of integrands=
.  This system uses over 6600 integration rules to compute integrals.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTERichScheibeAbbasi2018_55-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-FOOTNOTERichScheibeA=
bbasi2018-55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>  The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ram=
anujan%27s_master_theorem#Bracket_integration_method" title=3D"Ramanujan's =
master theorem"> method of brackets</a> is a generalization of Ramanujan's =
master theorem that can be applied to a wide range of univariate and multiv=
ariate integrals.  A set of rules are applied to the coefficients and expon=
ential terms of the integrand's power series expansion to determine the int=
egral.  The method is closely related to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Mellin_transform" title=3D"Mellin transform">Mellin transform</a=
>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGonzalezJiuMoll2020_56-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGonzal=
ezJiuMoll2020-56"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>55<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Numerical">Numerical</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DIntegral&amp;actio=
n=3Dedit&amp;section=3D32" title=3D"Edit section: Numerical"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerical_integratio=
n" title=3D"Numerical integration">Numerical integration</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Numerical_quadrature_4up.png"=
 class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wik=
ipedia/commons/thumb/a/a0/Numerical_quadrature_4up.png/250px-Numerical_quad=
rature_4up.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"250" class=3D"mw=
-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1260" data-file-height=3D"1260"></a><figc=
aption>Numerical quadrature methods: rectangle method, trapezoidal rule, Ro=
mberg's method (at varying piece count), Gaussian quadrature</figcaption></=
figure>
<p>Definite integrals may be approximated using several methods of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerical_integration" title=3D"Numerical=
 integration">numerical integration</a>. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Rectangle_method" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rectangle metho=
d">rectangle method</a> relies on dividing the region under the function in=
to a series of rectangles corresponding to function values and multiplies b=
y the step width to find the sum. A better approach, the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoidal_rule" title=3D"Trapezoidal rule">trapezo=
idal rule</a>, replaces the rectangles used in a Riemann sum with trapezoid=
s. The trapezoidal rule weights the first and last values by one half, then=
 multiplies by the step width to obtain a better approximation.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-57" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In=
tegral#cite_note-57"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>56<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The idea behind the trapezoidal rule, that=
 more accurate approximations to the function yield better approximations t=
o the integral, can be carried further: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Simpson%27s_rule" title=3D"Simpson's rule">Simpson's rule</a> approxi=
mates the integrand by a piecewise quadratic function.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5=
8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#ci=
te_note-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>57<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Riemann sums, the trapezoidal rule, and Simpson's rule are examples =
of a family of quadrature rules called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Newton%E2%80%93Cotes_formulas" title=3D"Newton=E2=80=93Cotes formu=
las">Newton=E2=80=93Cotes formulas</a>. The degree <span class=3D"texhtml m=
var" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> Newton=E2=80=93Cotes quadrature =
rule approximates the polynomial on each subinterval by a degree <i><span c=
lass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span></i> polynomial.=
 This polynomial is chosen to interpolate the values of the function on the=
 interval.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-59" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-59"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>58<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Higher degree Newton=
=E2=80=93Cotes approximations can be more accurate, but they require more f=
unction evaluations, and they can suffer from numerical inaccuracy due to <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Runge%27s_phenomenon" title=3D"Rung=
e's phenomenon">Runge's phenomenon</a>. One solution to this problem is <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clenshaw%E2%80%93Curtis_quadrature" t=
itle=3D"Clenshaw=E2=80=93Curtis quadrature">Clenshaw=E2=80=93Curtis quadrat=
ure</a>, in which the integrand is approximated by expanding it in terms of=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chebyshev_polynomials" title=3D"C=
hebyshev polynomials">Chebyshev polynomials</a>.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Romberg%27s_method" title=
=3D"Romberg's method">Romberg's method</a> halves the step widths increment=
ally, giving trapezoid approximations denoted by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i=
>T</i>(<i>h</i><sub>0</sub>)</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>T</i>(<i>h<=
/i><sub>1</sub>)</span>, and so on, where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>h</i><=
sub><i>k</i>+1</sub></span> is half of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>h</i><sub=
><i>k</i></sub></span>. For each new step size, only half the new function =
values need to be computed; the others carry over from the previous size. I=
t then <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interpolation" title=3D"Int=
erpolation">interpolate</a> a polynomial through the approximations, and ex=
trapolate to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>T</i>(0)</span>. <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaussian_quadrature" title=3D"Gaussian quadrature">G=
aussian quadrature</a> evaluates the function at the roots of a set of <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthogonal_polynomials" title=3D"Ortho=
gonal polynomials">orthogonal polynomials</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-60" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-=
60"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>59<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> An <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;=
">n</span>-point Gaussian method is exact for polynomials of degree up to <=
span class=3D"texhtml">2<i>n</i> =E2=88=92 1</span>.
</p><p>The computation of higher-dimensional integrals (for example, volume=
 calculations) makes important use of such alternatives as <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_integration" title=3D"Monte Carlo inte=
gration">Monte Carlo integration</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-61" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral#cite_note-61"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>60<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Mechanical">Mechanical</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DIntegral&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D33" title=3D"Edit section: Mechanical"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The area of an arbitrary two-dimensional shape can be determined using a=
 measuring instrument called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plani=
meter" title=3D"Planimeter">planimeter</a>. The volume of irregular objects=
 can be measured with precision by the fluid <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Displacement_(fluid)" title=3D"Displacement (fluid)">displaced</=
a> as the object is submerged.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Geometrical">Geometrical</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DIntegral&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D34" title=3D"Edit section: Geometrical"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadrature_(mathemat=
ics)" title=3D"Quadrature (mathematics)">Quadrature (mathematics)</a></div>
<p>Area can sometimes be found via <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Geometrical" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Geometrical">geometrical</a> <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compass-and-straightedge_constructi=
on" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Compass-and-straightedge construction">c=
ompass-and-straightedge constructions</a> of an equivalent <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square" title=3D"Square">square</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Integration_by_differentiat=
ion">Integration by differentiation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DIntegral&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D35" title=
=3D"Edit section: Integration by differentiation"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Kempf, Jackson and Morales demonstrated mathematical relations that allo=
w an integral to be calculated by means of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Derivative" title=3D"Derivative">differentiation</a>. Their calcul=
us involves the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dirac_delta_functi=
on" title=3D"Dirac delta function">Dirac delta function</a> and the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partial_derivative" title=3D"Partial deri=
vative">partial derivative</a> operator <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe=
-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml=
-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/=
MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \partial _{x}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
